# Agent Manager Rules

## Purpose
Rules governing the Agent Manager agent and its operations within the agent ecosystem.

### Primary Functions
- Define agent creation and modification protocols
- Establish agent lifecycle management procedures
- Govern agent capability evolution and specialization
- Ensure consistency across agent implementations

## Creation & Modification Protocol

### Security Requirements
1. All agent management operations require authentication and authorization
2. Role-based access control (RBAC) governs all operations
3. Cryptographic signatures verify system integrity
4. Goal integrity checks prevent hijacking attacks
5. All operations require appropriate permissions based on sensitivity

### Agent Blueprint Requirements
1. Must include clear objective and scope definition
2. Requires defined capabilities and limitations
3. Must specify delegation patterns and relationships
4. Requires output format specification
5. Must document dependencies and integration points

### Naming Convention
- Single purpose: `agent-name` (e.g., `debug`, `code-reviewer`)
- Multi-purpose: `domain-specialist` (e.g., `frontend-specialist`, `database-specialist`)
- Ecosystem management: `meta-agent-{function}` (e.g., `meta-agent-architect`)

## Modification Protocol

### Versioning
- Major version change: API/contract breaking changes
- Minor version change: New capabilities, backward compatible
- Patch version change: Bug fixes, documentation updates

### Backward Compatibility
- Must maintain existing delegation patterns
- Cannot remove existing capabilities without deprecation period
- Must provide migration path for deprecated features

## Authentication & Authorization

### Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
- Define roles with specific permissions for agent management
- Implement hierarchical role structure: Admin, Editor, Viewer
- Admin: Full access to create, modify, delete agents
- Editor: Create and modify agents, cannot delete
- Viewer: Read-only access to agent specifications

### Permission System
- agent.create: Create new agents
- agent.update: Modify existing agents
- agent.delete: Delete agents (requires dual approval)
- agent.read: View agent specifications
- system.config: Modify system-level configurations

### Authentication Requirements
- All agent management operations require valid authentication token
- Tokens must be cryptographically signed and have limited lifespan
- Multi-factor authentication required for admin operations
- All authentication attempts logged for audit purposes

## Ownership and Delegation

### Exclusive Ownership
- `agents/{name}.md`: Agent specification
- `rules/{name}/`: Agent-specific rules
- `skills/{name}/`: Agent-specific skills

### Delegation Rules
- Agent creation: `skills/subagent-factory` (requires agent.create permission)
- Agent updates: `agent-architect` (requires agent.update permission)
- Agent deprecation: `agent-manager` + `orchestrator` (requires agent.delete and dual approval)

## Security Controls

### Goal Integrity Verification
- All system prompts must be cryptographically signed
- Goal integrity checks at each planning step verify alignment with original objectives
- System instructions isolated from user-supplied content
- Monitor for goal drift by comparing current actions against signed objectives
- Reject any operations that deviate from approved goals without explicit approval

### System Protection
- Signed system prompts cannot be overridden by user input
- Parameterized tool inputs prevent injection attacks
- Allow-lists for tool parameters with valid ranges and formats
- Tool-level authorization validates permissions independently
- Sandboxed execution environment with principle of least privilege
- Validate and sanitize all outputs before consumption
- Structured output formats with JSON schema validation

## Quality Gates

### Pre-Creation Checklist
- [ ] Clear use case justification
- [ ] No existing agent can fulfill the requirement
- [ ] Well-defined scope and boundaries
- [ ] Documented capabilities and limitations
- [ ] Integration plan with existing agents
- [ ] Security review completed
- [ ] Appropriate permissions identified

### Pre-Modification Checklist
- [ ] Impact assessment on existing workflows
- [ ] Backward compatibility analysis
- [ ] Migration path definition
- [ ] Deprecation plan for removed features
- [ ] Documentation update plan
- [ ] Security implications analyzed
- [ ] Permission changes documented

## Anti-Patterns

### Forbidden Practices
- Creating agents for one-off tasks
- Duplicating existing agent capabilities
- Overlapping ownership with other agents
- Creating circular dependencies between agents
- Violating backward compatibility without proper deprecation

### Code Smells
- Agents with too broad capabilities (God objects)
- Agents with overlapping responsibilities
- Agents without clear ownership boundaries
- Agents without proper versioning strategy
- Agents without documented deprecation policy